\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Orthogonalized Sectoral Factor Influence on VIX Regime Transitions**

This study identifies the predictive relationship between daily changes in `^VIX` and latent sectoral factors derived from the 10-sector ETF universe (excluding `XLC` due to historical data absence). To mitigate multicollinearity and the curse of dimensionality, we perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the log-returns of the 10 stable sector ETFs, extracting the top three orthogonal components that capture systemic cross-sectoral dynamics. We then deploy a Factor-Augmented Regression model to estimate the sensitivity of `^VIX` innovations at $t+1$ to shocks in these orthogonal components, while controlling for the contemporaneous market beta of `^GSPC`. By isolating the residual variance of `^VIX` not explained by the primary market factor, we quantify the specific "volatility-responsiveness" of individual sectoral clusters. This framework avoids the noise-propagation issues of high-dimensional VARs while providing a statistically rigorous measure of how specific equity-market sub-sectors lead or lag implied volatility spikes. The model is validated using a rolling-window backtest to assess the stationarity of these factor-volatility sensitivities across the 2015–2026 period.
\end{IDEA}


